ACCORDION_ANSWER_1: EtherScan is a blockchain explorer and analytics platform for Ethereum. It allows you to explore and search the Ethereum blockchain, view transaction details, check smart contract code, and more.
ACCORDION_QUESTION_2: How can I find new Ethereum transactions?
ACCORDION_ANSWER_2: EtherScan has a 'Latest Transactions' section that shows the most recent transactions on the Ethereum network in real-time. You can also set up alerts to be notified of new transactions to specific wallet addresses or contracts.
ACCORDION_ANSWER_3: Yes, EtherScan is free to use for basic features like viewing transactions and balances. However, there are paid plans available for advanced data APIs and analytics tools for developers and businesses.
ACCORDION_QUESTION_4: Is my data private when using EtherScan?
ACCORDION_ANSWER_4: All data on the Ethereum blockchain is public by design. EtherScan does not collect or store any private user data beyond basic analytics. However, you should still take precautions like using a secure wallet and VPN.
FAQ_SUBTITLE_PLACEHOLDER_TEXT: Get answers to common questions about our app
FAQ_PLACEHOLDER_ANSWER_TEXT_1: Our app allows you to easily explore and monitor new transactions on the Ethereum blockchain in real-time.
FAQ_PLACEHOLDER_ANSWER_TEXT_2: We connect directly to Ethereum nodes to stream incoming transactions as they get added to new blocks. Our algorithms quickly parse and index this data for fast querying.
FAQ_PLACEHOLDER_QUESTION_TEXT_3: What kind of transactions can I see?
FAQ_PLACEHOLDER_ANSWER_TEXT_3: You can view details on all kinds of Ethereum transactions including token transfers, smart contract deployments/executions, and basic ETH transfers between wallets.
FAQ_PLACEHOLDER_ANSWER_TEXT_4: Yes, our basic transaction monitoring is free to use. We offer premium paid plans with additional filtering, notification, and data export features.
FAQ_PLACEHOLDER_ANSWER_TEXT_5: Just sign up for a free account on our website. The onboarding flow will guide you through connecting to the Ethereum networks you want to monitor.
